4 - Pillars of OOPs:
1) Inheritance: Inheritance is a fundamental concept in OOPs that allows a new class (called a subclass or child class) to inherit

super class or parent class - the class being inherited from
sub class or child class - the class that inherits from the another class

extends - keyword used to inherit a class

Types of Inheritance:
1) Single Inheritance: A subclass inherits from a single superclass.
2) Multilevel Inheritance: A subclass inherits from a superclass, which in turn inherits from
3) Hierarchical Inheritance: Multiple subclasses inherit from a single superclass.
4) Hybrid Inheritance: A combination of multiple types of inheritance
5) Multiple Inheritance: A subclass inherits from multiple superclasses (not supported in Java, but can be achieved through interfaces).


Polymorphism: Polymorphism is the ability of an object to take on many forms. It allows objects of different classes to be treated as objects of a common superclass.
Polymorphism is achieved through method overriding and method overloading.

Poly - Many
morph - Forms

Overloading - same method name with different parameters
    easy to remember method name but different implementation based on parameters

Overriding - same method name with same parameters but different implementation in subclass

parent
marriage() -> abc
gift()

child
marriage() -> xyz

Abstraction

Abstract Class - An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated and is meant to be subclassed. It can contain abstract methods (methods without implementation) that must be implemented by the subclasses.
0-100% abstraction - abstract class
(Abstract class can have both abstract and non-abstract methods)
Incomplete class - cannot create object of abstract class
Abstract class can have constructor and static methods


100% abstraction - interface
Interface - An interface is a reference type in Java that is similar to a class but can only contain abstract methods, default methods, static methods, and constant variables. It is used to specify a contract that classes must adhere to.


Encapsulation - Encapsulation is the process of bundling data (attributes) and methods (behaviors) that operate on the data into a single unit, called a class. It also involves hiding the internal details of an object and providing a public interface for interacting with it.

private data members - cannot be accessed directly from outside the class
public methods - can be accessed from outside the class to interact with the private data members









